# A01.1.00.032
- ## Term
	- EN: "Pelvic girdle"
	- LA: "Cingulum pelvicum"
	- ES: "Cintura pélvica"
- ## Definition:
	- "a bony or cartilaginous arch that supports the hind limbs of a vertebrate, that corresponds to the shoulder girdle of the forelimbs but is usually more rigid and firmly attached to the spinal column, and that consists in lower forms of a single cartilage which is replaced in higher forms including humans by paired hip bones articulating solidly with the sacrum dorsally and with one another at the pubic symphysis" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.033
- ## Term
	- EN: "Buttocks"
	- LA: "Nates"
	- ES: "Nalgas"
- ## Definition:
	- "the back of a hip that forms one of the fleshy parts on which a person sits","the seat of the body; also : the corresponding part of a quadruped : rump" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.034
- ## Term
	- EN: "Hip"
	- LA: "Coxa"
	- ES: "Cadera"
- ## Definition:
	- "the laterally projecting region of each side of the lower or posterior part of the mammalian trunk formed by the lateral parts of the pelvis and upper part of the femur together with the fleshy parts covering them","hip joint" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.035
- ## Term
	- EN: "Thigh"
	- LA: "Femur"
	- ES: "Muslo"
- ## Definition:
	- "the proximal segment of the vertebrate hind or lower limb extending from the hip to the knee and supported by a single large bone","the segment of the leg immediately distal to the thigh in a bird or in a quadruped in which the true thigh is obscured","the femur of an insect" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.036
- ## Term
	- EN: "Knee"
	- LA: "Genu"
	- ES: "Rodilla"
- ## Definition:
	- "a joint in the middle part of the human leg that is the articulation between the femur, tibia, and patella \u2014called also knee joint","the part of the leg that includes this joint","the joint in the hind leg of a 4-footed vertebrate that corresponds to the human knee" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.037
- ## Term
	- EN: "Posterior part of knee"
	- LA: "Poples"
	- ES: "Fosa poplítea"
- ## Definition: 

# A01.1.00.038
- ## Term
	- EN: "Leg"
	- LA: "Crus"
	- ES: "Pierna"
- ## Definition:
	- "a limb of an animal used especially for supporting the body and for walking: as","either of the two lower human limbs that extend from the top of the thigh to the foot and especially the part between the knee and the ankle","any of the rather generalized segmental appendages of an arthropod used in walking and crawling" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.039
- ## Term
	- EN: "Calf"
	- LA: "Sura"
	- ES: "Pantorilla"
- ## Definition:
	- "the fleshy back part of the leg below the knee" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.040
- ## Term
	- EN: "Foot"
	- LA: "Pes"
	- ES: "Pies"
- ## Definition:
	- "the terminal part of the vertebrate leg upon which an individual stands","any of various units of length based on the length of the human foot; especially : a unit equal to 1\/3 yard or 12 inches or 30.48 centimeters \u2014plural foot used between a number and a noun \u2014plural feet or foot used between a number and an adjective" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.041
- ## Term
	- EN: "Ankle"
	- LA: "Tarsus"
	- ES: "Tarso"
- ## Definition:
	- "the joint between the foot and the leg that constitutes in humans a ginglymus joint between the tibia and fibula above and the talus below \u2014called also ankle joint","the region of the ankle joint","the joint between the cannon bone and pastern (as in the horse)" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.042
- ## Term
	- EN: "Heel"
	- LA: "Calx"
	- ES: "Talón"
- ## Definition:
	- "the back of the human foot below the ankle and behind the arch","the back of the hind limb of other vertebrates homologous with the human heel","an anatomical structure suggestive of the human heel: as" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.043
- ## Term
	- EN: "Metatarsus"
	- LA: "Metatarsus"
	- ES: "Metatarso"
- ## Definition:
	- "the part of the human foot or of the hind foot in quadrupeds that is between the tarsus and phalanges, contains when all the digits are present (as in humans) five more or less elongated bones but is modified in many animals with loss or reduction of some bones or fusing of others, and in humans forms the instep" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A01.1.00.044
- ## Term
	- EN: "Sole"
	- LA: "Planta"
	- ES: "Planta"
- ## Definition:
	- "the undersurface of a foot","the somewhat concave plate of moderately dense horn that covers the lower surface of the coffin bone of the horse, partly surrounds the frog, and is bounded externally by the wall" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.007
- ## Term
	- EN: "Periosteum"
	- LA: "Periosteum"
	- ES: "Periostio"
- ## Definition:
	- "the membrane of connective tissue that closely invests all bones except at the articular surfaces" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.008
- ## Term
	- EN: "Perichondrium"
	- LA: "Perichondrium"
	- ES: "Pericondrio"
- ## Definition:
	- "the membrane of fibrous connective tissue that invests cartilage except at joints" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.009
- ## Term
	- EN: "Axial skeleton"
	- LA: "Skeleton axiale"
	- ES: "Esqueleto axial"
- ## Definition:
	- "the skeleton of the trunk and head" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.010
- ## Term
	- EN: "Appendicular skeleton"
	- LA: "Skeleton appendiculare"
	- ES: "Esqueleto apendicular"
- ## Definition: 

# A02.0.00.011
- ## Term
	- EN: "Long bone"
	- LA: "Os longum"
	- ES: "Hueso largo"
- ## Definition:
	- "any of the elongated bones supporting a vertebrate limb and consisting of an essentially cylindrical shaft that contains bone marrow and ends in enlarged heads for articulation with other bones" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.012
- ## Term
	- EN: "Short bone"
	- LA: "Os breve"
	- ES: "Hueso corto"
- ## Definition:
	- "a bone (as of the tarsus or carpus) that is of approximately equal length in all dimensions" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.013
- ## Term
	- EN: "Flat bone"
	- LA: "Os planum"
	- ES: "Hueso plano"
- ## Definition:
	- "any of various bones (as of the skull, the jaw, the pelvis, or the rib cage) not rounded in cross section" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.014
- ## Term
	- EN: "Irregular bone"
	- LA: "Os irregulare"
	- ES: "Hueso irregular"
- ## Definition:

	- ES: "Hueso neumatizado"
- ## Definition: 

# A02.0.00.016

	- LA: "Os sesamoideum"
	- ES: "Hueso sesamoideo"
- ## Definition: 

# A02.0.00.017
- ## Term
	- EN: "Diaphysis"
	- LA: "Diaphysis"
	- ES: "Diáfisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "the shaft of a long bone" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.018
- ## Term
	- EN: "Epiphysis"
	- LA: "Epiphysis"
	- ES: "Epífisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "a part or process of a bone that ossifies separately and later becomes ankylosed to the main part of the bone; especially : the usually rounded end of the shaft of a long bone that is composed mainly of cancellous bone covered by a thin layer of compact bone","pineal gland" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.019
- ## Term
	- EN: "Epiphysial cartilage"
	- LA: "Cartilago epiphysialis"
	- ES: "Cartílago epifisario"
- ## Definition:

	- LA: "Lamina epiphysialis"
	- ES: "Lámina epifisaria"
- ## Definition: 

# A02.0.00.021
- ## Term
	- EN: "Epiphysial line"
	- LA: "Linea epiphysialis"
	- ES: "Línea epifisaria"
- ## Definition: 

# A02.0.00.022
- ## Term
	- EN: "Metaphysis"
	- LA: "Metaphysis"
	- ES: "Metáfisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "the transitional zone at which the diaphysis and epiphysis of a bone come together" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.023
- ## Term
	- EN: "Apophysis"
	- LA: "Apophysis"
	- ES: "Apófisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "an expanded or projecting part especially of an organism" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.024
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tuber"
	- LA: "Tuber"
	- ES: "Eminencia"
- ## Definition:
	- "an anatomical prominence : tuberosity" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.025
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tubercle"
	- LA: "Tuberculum"
	- ES: "Tubérculo"
- ## Definition:
	- "a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as","a prominence on the crown of a molar tooth","a small rough prominence (as the greater tubercle or adductor tubercle) on a bone usually being smaller than a tuberosity and serving for the attachment of one or more muscles or ligaments" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.026
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tuberosity"
	- LA: "Tuberositas"
	- ES: "Tuberosidad"
- ## Definition:
	- "a rounded prominence; especially : a large prominence on a bone usually serving for the attachment of muscles or ligaments" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.027
- ## Term
	- EN: "Eminence"
	- LA: "Eminentia"
	- ES: "Eminencia"
- ## Definition:
	- "a protuberance or projection on a bodily part and especially a bone" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.028
- ## Term
	- EN: "Process"
	- LA: "Processus"
	- ES: "Proceso"
- ## Definition:
	- "a natural progressively continuing operation or development marked by a series of gradual changes that succeed one another in a relatively fixed way and lead toward a particular result or end","a natural continuing activity or function","a prominent or projecting part of an organism or organic structure" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.029
- ## Term
	- EN: "Condyle"
	- LA: "Condylus"
	- ES: "Cóndilo"
- ## Definition:
	- "an articular prominence of a bone \u2014used chiefly of such as occur in pairs resembling a pair of knuckles (as those of the occipital bone for articulation with the atlas, those at the distal end of the humerus and femur, and those of the lower jaw)" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.030
- ## Term
	- EN: "Epicondyle"
	- LA: "Epicondylus"
	- ES: "Epicóndilo"
- ## Definition:
	- "any of several prominences on the distal part of a long bone serving for the attachment of muscles and ligaments:","one on the outer aspect of the distal part of the humerus or proximal to the lateral condyle of the femur \u2014called also lateral epicondyle","a larger and more prominent one on the inner aspect of the distal part of the humerus or proximal to the medial condyle of the femur \u2014called also medial epicondyle" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A02.0.00.031
- ## Term
	- EN: "Crest"
	- LA: "Crista"
	- ES: "Cresta"
- ## Definition:
	- "a showy tuft or process on the head of an animal and especially a bird","a process or prominence on a part of an animal body: as","the upper curve or ridge of the neck of a quadruped (as a horse); also : the mane borne on such a crest" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- EN: "Pubis"
	- LA: "Os pubis"
	- ES: "Hueso pubis"
- ## Definition:
	- "the ventral and anterior of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis that in humans consists of two rami diverging posteriorly from the region of the pubic symphysis with the superior ramus extending to the acetabulum of which it forms a part and uniting there with the ilium and ischium and the inferior ramus extending below the obturator foramen where it unites with the ischium \u2014called also pubic bone" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.2.01.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Platysma"
	- LA: "Platysma"
	- ES: "Platisma"
- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Configuration
			- Broad muscle
		- Conformation
			- Origin
				- Scapular girdle
				- Fascia covering deltoid
				- Fascia covering pectorals major
			- Insertion
				- Mental skin
				- Inferior border of mandible
				- Lower face skin
		- Action
			- Tense skin of neck
			- Draw corners of mouth inferiorly
		- Arteries
			- Submental artery
			- Supraescapular artery
		- Nerves
			- Cervical branch of facial nerve
- ## Definition:
	- "a broad thin layer of muscle that is situated on each side of the neck immediately under the superficial fascia belonging to the group of facial muscles, that is innervated by the facial nerve, and that draws the lower lip and the corner of the mouth to the side and down and when moved forcefully expands the neck and draws its skin upward" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.2.01.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Longus colli"
	- LA: "M. longus colli"
	- ES: "Músculo largo del cuello"
- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Constitution
			- Striated muscle tissue
		- Configuration
			- Long triangular muscle
		- Conformation
			- Longitudinal portion
				- Origin
					- Anterior of tubercle C4-C6 vertebrae
					- Body of T1-T3 vertebrae
				- Insertion
					- Body of C2-C4 vertebrae
			- Superolateral portion
				- Origin
					- Transverse process of C3-C5
				- Insertion
					- Anterior tubercle of atlas
			- Inferolateral portion
				- Origin
					- Body of T1-T3 vertebrae
				- Insertion
					- Transverse process of C5-C7 vertebrae
		- Arteries
			- Ascending cervical artery
			- Inferior thyroid artery
		- Nerves
			- Anterior rami of C2-C6 spinal nerves
		- Action
			- Flexion of neck
			- Ipsilateral rotation of neck
- ## Definition:

		- Configuration

		- Conformation
			- Origin

			- Insertion

			- Inferior thyroid artery
		- Nerves

		- Action
			- Flexion of head
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle of either side of the front and upper portion of the neck that arises from the third to sixth cervical vertebrae, is inserted into the basilar portion of the occipital bone, and bends the neck forward" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.4.01.007
- ## Term
	- EN: "Subclavius"
	- LA: "M. subclavius"
	- ES: "M. subclavio"
- ## Definition:
	- "a small muscle on each side of the body that arises from the junction of the first rib and its cartilage, inserts into the inferior surface of the clavicle, and acts to stabilize the clavicle by depressing and drawing forward its lateral end during movements of the shoulder joint" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.4.01.008
- ## Term
	- EN: "Serratus anterior"
	- LA: "M. serratus anterior"
	- ES: "M. serrato anterior"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thin muscular sheet of the thorax that arises from the first eight or nine ribs and from the intercostal muscles between them, is inserted into the ventral side of the medial margin of the scapula, and acts to stabilize the scapula by holding it against the chest wall and to rotate it in raising the arm" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.4.01.009
- ## Term
	- EN: "Levatores costarum"
	- LA: "Mm. levatores costarum"
	- ES: "Músculos elevadores de las costillas"
- ## Definition:
	- "a series of 12 muscles on each side that arise from the transverse processes of the seventh cervical and upper 11 thoracic vertebrae, that pass obliquely downward and laterally to insert into the outer surface of the rib immediately below or in the case of the lowest four muscles of the series divide into two fasciculi of which one inserts as described and the other inserts into the second rib below, and that raise the ribs increasing the volume of the thoracic cavity and extend, bend, and rotate the spinal column" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.4.01.016
- ## Term
	- EN: "Transversus thoracis"
	- LA: "M. transversus thoracis"
	- ES: "M. transverso del tórax"

        - Nerves
			- Intercostal nerve

# A04.4.02.005
- ## Term
	- EN: "Median arcuate ligament"
	- LA: "Lig. arcuatum medianum"
	- ES: "Ligamento arcuato medio"
- ## Definition:
	- "a tendinous arch that lies in front of the aorta and that connects the attachments of the lumbar portion of the diaphragm to the lumbar vertebrae on each side" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.4.02.006
- ## Term
	- EN: "Medial arcuate ligament"
	- LA: "Lig. arcuatum mediale"
	- ES: "Ligament arcuato medial"
- ## Definition:
	- "an arched band of fascia that covers the upper part of the psoas major muscle, extends from the body of the first or second lumbar vertebra to the transverse process of the first and sometimes also the second lumbar vertebra, and provides attachment for part of the lumbar portion of the diaphragm" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.4.02.007
- ## Term
	- EN: "Lateral arcuate ligament"
	- LA: "Lig. arcuatum laterale"
	- ES: "Ligamento arcuato lateral"
- ## Definition:
	- "a fascial band that is formed by part of the quadratus lumborum muscle, extends from the tip of the transverse process of the first lumbar vertebra to the twelfth rib, and provides attachment for part of the diaphragm" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

        - Configuration
			- Long muscle
        - Conformation
			- Origin

			- Insertion
				- 5th-6th costal artilage
			- Tendinous intesections

	- LA: "M. transversus abdominis"
	- ES: "Músculo transverso del abdomen"
- ## Data
    - Anatomy
        - Constitution
			- Striated muscle tissue
        - Configuration
			- Broad muscle
        - Conformation
			- Origin
				- 6th-12th ribs
				- Costal process of lumbar vertebrae
				- Iliac crest
			- Insertion
				- Transversus abdominis aponeurosis
				- Inguinal falx
					- Pubic tubercle
				- Deep inguinal ring
        - Arteries
			- Posterior intercostal arteries
			- Subcostal artery
			- Superior epigastric artery
			- Inferior epigastric artery

			- Posterior lumbar arteries

        - Action

	- LA: "M. teres minor"

- ## Definition:
	- "a long cylindrical muscle that arises from the upper two-thirds of the axillary border of the scapula, passes behind the long head of the triceps to insert chiefly on the greater tubercle of the humerus, contributes to the formation of the rotator cuff of the shoulder, and acts to rotate the arm laterally and draw the humerus toward the glenoid fossa" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.011

	- LA: "M. teres major"

# A04.6.02.012

	- LA: "M. subscapularis"
	- ES: "Músculo subescapular"

# A04.6.02.013
- ## Term
	- EN: "Biceps brachii"
	- LA: "M. biceps brachii"
	- ES: "Músculo bíceps braquial"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle having two heads: as","the large flexor muscle of the front of the upper arm arising by its short head from the coracoid process and by its long head from the upper margin of the glenoid cavity and being inserted into the tuberosity of the radius","the large flexor muscle of the back of the upper leg that arises by its long head from the tuberosity of the ischium and by its short head from the shaft of the femur, that is inserted into the head of the fibula, its tendon forming the outer hamstring, and that flexes the leg on the thigh and extends the thigh on the trunk" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- LA: "M. pronator quadratus"

	- LA: "M. brachioradialis"

# A04.6.02.040

	- ES: "Músculo extensor radial largo del carpo"

	- EN: "Supinator"
	- LA: "M. supinator"
	- ES: "Músculo supinador"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle that produces the motion of supination; specifically : a deeply situated muscle of the forearm that arises in two layers from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and adjacent parts of the ligaments and bones of the elbow and that passes over the head of the radius to insert into its neck and the lateral surface of its shaft" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.049
- ## Term
	- EN: "Abductor pollicis longus"
	- LA: "M. abductor pollicis longus"
	- ES: "Músculo abductor largo del pulgar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle of the forearm that abducts the thumb and wrist" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.050
- ## Term
	- EN: "Extensor pollicis brevis"
	- LA: "M. extensor pollicis brevis"
	- ES: "Músculo extensor corto del pulgar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle that arises from the dorsal surface of the radius, extends the first phalanx of the thumb, and adducts the hand" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.051
- ## Term
	- EN: "Extensor pollicis longus"
	- LA: "M. extensor pollicis longus"
	- ES: "Músculo extensor largo del pulgar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle that arises dorsolaterally from the middle part of the ulna, extends the second phalanx of the thumb, and abducts the hand" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.052
- ## Term
	- EN: "Extensor indicis"
	- LA: "M. extensor indicis"
	- ES: "Músculo extensor del índice"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thin muscle that arises from the ulna in the more distal part of the forearm and extends the index finger" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.053
- ## Term
	- EN: "Palmaris brevis"
	- LA: "M. palmaris brevis"
	- ES: "Músculo palmar corto"
- ## Definition:
	- "a short transverse superficial muscle of the ulnar side of the palm of the hand that arises from the flexor retinaculum and palmar aponeurosis, inserts into the skin on the ulnar edge of the palm, and functions to tense and stabilize the palm (as in making a fist or catching a ball)" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.054
- ## Term
	- EN: "Abductor pollicis brevis"
	- LA: "M. abductor pollicis brevis"
	- ES: "Músculo abductor corto del pulgar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thin flat muscle of the hand that abducts the thumb at right angles to the plane of the palm" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.02.055
- ## Term
	- EN: "Flexor pollicis brevis"
	- LA: "M. flexor pollicis brevis"
	- ES: "Músculo flexor corto del pulgar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a short muscle of the palm that flexes and adducts the thumb" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- ES: "Músculo oponente del pulgar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a small triangular muscle of the hand that is located below the abductor pollicis brevis, arises from the trapezium and the flexor retinaculum of the hand, is inserted along the radial side of the metacarpal of the thumb, and functions to abduct, flex, and rotate the metacarpal of the thumb in opposing the thumb and fingers" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

- ## Term
	- EN: "Adductor pollicis"
	- LA: "M. adductor pollicis"
	- ES: "Músculo aductor del pulgar"
- ## Definition:

- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle of the hand that abducts the little finger and flexes the phalanx nearest the hand","a muscle of the foot that abducts the little toe" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- EN: "Flexor digiti minimi brevis"

- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle of the ulnar side of the palm of the hand that flexes the little finger","a muscle of the sole of the foot that flexes the first proximal phalanx of the little toe" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.03.010
- ## Term
	- EN: "Extensor retinaculum"
	- LA: "Retinaculum musculorum extensorum"
	- ES: "Retináculo extensor"
- ## Definition:
	- "either of two fibrous bands of fascia crossing the front of the ankle:","a lower band that is attached laterally to the superior aspect of the calcaneus and passes medially to divide in the shape of a Y and that passes over or both over and under the tendons of the extensor muscles at the ankle \u2014called also inferior extensor retinaculum","an upper band passing over and binding down the tendons of the tibialis anterior, extensor hallucis longus, extensor digitorum longus, and peroneus tertius just above the ankle joint \u2014called also superior extensor retinaculum, transverse crural ligament" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.03.011
- ## Term
	- EN: "Superficial transverse metacarpal ligament"
	- LA: "Lig. metacarpale transversum superficiale"
	- ES: "Ligamento metacarpiano transverso superficial"
- ## Definition:
	- "a transverse ligamentous band across the palm of the hand in the superficial fascia at the base of the fingers \u2014called also superficial transverse ligament" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.03.012
- ## Term
	- EN: "Palmar aponeurosis"
	- LA: "Aponeurosis palmaris"
	- ES: "Aponeurosis palmar"
- ## Definition:
	- "an aponeurosis of the palm of the hand that consists of a superficial longitudinal layer continuous with the tendon of the palmaris longus and of a deeper transverse layer \u2014called also palmar fascia" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.6.03.013
- ## Term
	- EN: "Flexor retinaculum"
	- LA: "Retinaculum musculorum flexorum"
	- ES: "Retináculo flexor"
- ## Definition:
	- "a fibrous band of fascia on the medial side of the ankle that extends downward from the medial malleolus of the tibia to the calcaneus and that covers over the bony grooves containing the tendons of the flexor muscles, the posterior tibial artery and vein, and the tibial nerve as they pass into the sole of the foot","a fibrous band of fascia on the palm side of the wrist and base of the hand that forms the roof of the carpal tunnel and covers the tendons of the flexor muscles and the median nerve as they pass into the hand \u2014called also transverse carpal ligament" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Muscles"
	- LA: "Musculi"
	- ES: "Músculos"
- ## Definition:
	- "a body tissue consisting of long cells that contract when stimulated and produce motion","an organ that is essentially a mass of muscle tissue attached at either end to a fixed point and that by contracting moves or checks the movement of a body part" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Iliopsoas"
	- LA: "M. iliopsoas"
	- ES: "Músculo iliopsoas"
- ## Data
    - Anatomy
        - Constitution
			- Striated muscle tissue
        - Configuration
			- Long muscle
        - Conformation
            - Psoas major
			- Iliacus
        - Arteries
        - Nerves
        - Action
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle consisting of the iliacus and psoas major muscles" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.003
- ## Term
	- EN: "Iliacus"
	- LA: "M. iliacus"
	- ES: "Músculo iliaco"
- ## Data
    - Anatomy
        - Constitution
			- Striated muscle tissue
        - Configuration
			- Long muscle
        - Conformation
            - Origin
				- Iliac fossa
				- Iliolumbar ligament
			- Insertion
				- Lesser trochanter
        - Arteries
			- Medial femoral circumflex artery
			- Iliolumbar artery
        - Nerves
			- Femoral nerve
        - Action
			- Flexor of hip
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle of the iliac region of the abdomen that flexes the thigh or bends the pelvis and lumbar region forward, has its origin from the iliac fossa, iliac crest, the base of the sacrum, and adjoining parts, and is inserted into the outer side of the tendon of the psoas major, the capsule of the hip joint, and the lesser trochanter of the femur" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.004
- ## Term
	- EN: "Psoas major"
	- LA: "M. psoas major"
	- ES: "Músculo psoas mayor"
- ## Data
    - Anatomy
        - Constitution
			- Striated muscle tissue
        - Configuration
			- Long muscle
        - Conformation
            - Origin
				- Body of vertebrae T12-L5
				- Intervertebral discs T12-L5
				- Costal process of lumbar vertebrae
			- Insertion
				- Lesser trochanter
       - Arteries
			- Iliolumbar artery
        - Nerves
			- Lumbar plexus
        - Action
			- Flexor of hip
- ## Definition:
	- "the larger of the two psoas muscles that arises from the anterolateral surfaces of the lumbar vertebrae, passes beneath the inguinal ligament to insert with the iliacus into the lesser trochanter of the femur, and serves especially to flex the thigh" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.005
- ## Term
	- EN: "(Psoas minor)"
	- LA: "(M. psoas minor)"
	- ES: "(Músculo psoas menor)"
- ## Data
    - Anatomy
        - Constitution
			- Striated muscle tissue
        - Configuration
			- Long muscle
        - Conformation
            - Origin
				- Body of vertebra T12
			- Insertion
				- Iliopubic eminence
       - Arteries
			- Iliolumbar artery
        - Nerves
			- Lumbar plexus
        - Action
			- Flexor of hip
- ## Definition:
	- "the smaller of the two psoas muscles that arises from the last dorsal and first lumbar vertebrae and inserts into the brim of the pelvis, that functions to flex the trunk and the lumbar spinal column, and that is often absent" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.006
- ## Term
	- EN: "Gluteus maximus"
	- LA: "M. gluteus maximus"
	- ES: "Músculo glúteo mayor"
- ## Definition:
	- "the outermost of the three muscles in each buttock that arises from the sacrum, coccyx, back part of the ilium and adjacent structures, that is inserted into the fascia lata of the thigh and the gluteal tuberosity of the femur, and that acts to extend and laterally rotate the thigh" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.007
- ## Term
	- EN: "Gluteus medius"
	- LA: "M. gluteus medius"
	- ES: "Músculo glúteo medio"
- ## Definition:
	- "the middle of the three muscles in each buttock that arises from the outer surface of the ilium, that is inserted into the greater trochanter of the femur, and that acts to abduct and medially rotate the thigh" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.008
- ## Term
	- EN: "Gluteus minimus"
	- LA: "M. gluteus minimus"
	- ES: "Músculo glúteo menor"
- ## Definition:
	- "the innermost of the three muscles in each buttock that arises from the outer surface of the ilium, that is inserted into the greater trochanter of the femur, and that acts similarly to the gluteus medius" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.009
- ## Term
	- EN: "Gluteal aponeurosis"
	- LA: "Aponeurosis glutea"
	- ES: "Aponeurosis glútea"
- ## Definition: 

# A04.7.02.010
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tensor fasciae latae"
	- LA: "M. tensor fasciae latae"
	- ES: "Músculo tensor de la fascia lata"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle that arises especially from the anterior part of the iliac crest and from the anterior superior iliac spine, is inserted into the iliotibial band of the fascia lata about one third of the way down the thigh, and acts to flex and abduct the thigh" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.011
- ## Term
	- EN: "Piriformis"
	- LA: "M. piriformis"
	- ES: "Músculo piriforme"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle that arises from the front of the sacrum, passes out of the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, is inserted into the upper border of the greater trochanter of the femur, and rotates the thigh laterally" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.012
- ## Term
	- EN: "Obturator internus"
	- LA: "M. obturatorius internus"
	- ES: "Músculo obturador interno"
- ## Definition:
	- "a muscle that arises from the margin of the obturator foramen and from the obturator membrane, that inserts into the greater trochanter of the femur by way of tendons passing through the greater sciatic foramen, and that acts to rotate the thigh laterally when it is extended and to abduct it in the flexed position" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A04.7.02.013
- ## Term
	- EN: "Gemellus superior"
	- LA: "M. gemellus superior"
	- ES: "Músculo gemelo superior"
- ## Definition:

# A05.4.01.001

		- Configuration

		- Conformation
			- Upper opening
			- Cervical part
			- Thoracic part

			- Abdominal part
			- Cardias
		- Arteries

- ## Term

- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Constitution
			- Pharynx
		- Configuration
			- Shape
				- Cylinder
			- External
				- Anterior facet
				- Posterior facet
			- Internal
		- Conformation
			- Skeleton
				- Cricoid cartilage
				- Thyroid cartilage
				- Epiglottic cartilage
				- Arytenoid cartilage
				- Corniculate cartilage
				- Cuneiform cartilage
			- Joints
				- Intrinsic
					- Cricothyroid joint
					- Median cricothyroid ligament
					- Crico-arytenoid joint
					- Cricopharyngeal ligament
					- Thyro-epiglottic ligament
					- Vocal ligament
					- Vestibular ligament
					- Quadrangular membrane
				- Extrinsic
					- Thyrohyoid membrane
					- Hyo-epiglottic ligament
					- Cricotracheal ligament
			- Muscles
				- Intrinsc
					- Cricothyroid muscle
					- Posterior crico-arytenoid
					- Lateral crico-arytenoid
					- Vocalis
					- Thyro-arytenoid
					- Oblique arytenoid
					- Transverse arytenoid
				- Extrinsic
					- Sternothyroid muscle
					- Thyrohyoid muscle
					- Stylopharyngeus
					- Palatopharyngeus
					- Inferior pharyngeal constrictor
		- Ateries
			- Superior laryngeal artery
			- Inferior laryngeal artery
			- Cricothyroid branch
		- Veins
			- Superior laryngeal vein
			- Inferior laryngeal vein
		- Nerves
			- Superior laryngeal nerve
			- Recurrent laryngeal nerve
- ## Definition:
	- "the modified upper part of the respiratory passage of air-breathing vertebrates that is bounded above by the glottis, is continuous below with the trachea, has a complex cartilaginous or bony skeleton capable of limited motion through the action of associated muscles, and in humans, most other mammals, and a few lower forms has a set of elastic vocal cords that play a major role in sound production and speech \u2014called also voice box" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

- ## Term
	- EN: "Endocrine glands"

- ## Definition:

# A11.1.00.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Pituitary gland"
	- LA: "Hypophysis"
	- ES: "Hipófisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "a small oval reddish gray very vascular endocrine organ that is attached to the infundibulum of the brain and occupies the sella turcica, that is present in all craniate vertebrates, that consists essentially of an epithelial anterior lobe derived from a diverticulum of the oral cavity and joined to a posterior lobe of nervous origin by a pars intermedia, and that has the several parts associated with various hormones which directly or indirectly affect most basic bodily functions and include substances exerting a controlling and regulating influence on other endocrine organs, controlling growth and development, or modifying the contraction of smooth muscle, renal function, and reproduction \u2014called also hypophysis, pituitary body" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A11.1.00.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Adenohypophysis"
	- LA: "Adenohypophysis"
	- ES: "Adenohipófisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "the anterior part of the pituitary gland that is derived from the embryonic pharynx and is primarily glandular in nature \u2014called also anterior lobe, anterior pituitary" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A11.1.00.003
- ## Term
	- EN: "Pars tuberalis"
	- LA: "Pars tuberalis"
	- ES: "Porción tuberal"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thin plate of cells that is an extension of the adenohypophysis on the ventral or anterior aspect of the infundibulum" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A11.1.00.004
- ## Term
	- EN: "Pars intermedia"
	- LA: "Pars intermedia"
	- ES: "Porción intermedia"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thin slip of tissue fused with the neurohypophysis and representing the remains of the posterior wall of Rathke\u0027s pouch" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A11.1.00.005
- ## Term
	- EN: "Pars distalis"
	- LA: "Pars distalis"
	- ES: "Porción distal"
- ## Definition:
	- "the anterior part of the adenohypophysis that is the major secretory part of the gland" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A11.1.00.006
- ## Term
	- EN: "Neurohypophysis"
	- LA: "Neurohypophysis"
	- ES: "Neurohipofisis"
- ## Definition:
	- "the portion of the pituitary gland that is derived from the embryonic brain, is composed of the infundibulum and neural lobe, and is concerned with the secretion of various hormones \u2014called also posterior pituitary gland" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A11.1.00.007

# A12.2.08.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Subclavian artery"
	- LA: "Arteria subclavia"
	- ES: "Arteria subclavia"
- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Constitution
			- Artery
		- Conformation
			- Origin
				- Left subclavian artery
					- Aortic arch
				- Right subclavian artery
					- Brachiocephalic trunk
			- Collaterals
				- Vertebral artery
				- Internal thoracic artery
				- Thyrocervical trunk
				- Costocervical trunk
				- Dorsal scapular artery
			- Terminals
				- Axillary artery
			- Segments
				- Prescalene part
				- Interscalene part
				- Postscalene part
- ## Definition:
	- "the proximal part of the main artery of the arm that arises on the right side from the brachiocephalic artery and on the left side from the arch of the aorta, that extends from its point of origin to the outer border of the first rib where it becomes the axillary artery and passes through the axilla and into the arm to become the brachial artery, and that supplies or gives off branches supplying the brain, neck, anterior wall of the thorax, and shoulder" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A12.2.08.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Vertebral artery"
	- LA: "Arteria vertebralis"
	- ES: "Arteria vertebral"
- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Constitution
			- Artery
		- Conformation
			- Origin
				- Subclavian artery
			- Collaterals
				- Spinal branches
				- Muscular branches
				- Meningeal branches
				- Posterior spinal artery
				- Posterior inferior cerebellar artery
				- Anterior spinal artery
			- Terminal
				- Basilar artery
- ## Definition:
	- "a large branch of the subclavian artery that ascends through the foramina in the transverse processes of each of the cervical vertebrae except the last one or two, enters the cranium through the foramen magnum, and unites with the corresponding artery of the opposite side to form the basilar artery" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A12.3.07.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Azygos vein"
	- LA: "Vena azygos"
	- ES: "Vena ácigos"
- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Constitution
		- Configuration
		- Conformation
			- Origin
				- Lateral root
					- Ascending lumbar vein
				- Medial root
					- Inferior vena cava
            - Collaterals
				- Posterior intercostal veins
				- Superior intercostal vein
				- Hemi-azygos vein
				- Accesory hemi-azygos vein
				- Esophagic veins
				- Pericardic veins
				- Posterior right bronchial vein
            - Joins
				- Superior vena cava
- ## Definition:
	- "any of a system of three veins which drain the thoracic wall and much of the abdominal wall and which form a collateral circulation when either the inferior or superior vena cava is obstructed; especially : a vein that receives blood from the right half of the thoracic and abdominal walls, ascends along the right side of the spinal column, and empties into the superior vena cava" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- "a large lymphatic vessel on each side of the body that receives lymph from the axilla and arms and that on the right side empties into the right lymphatic duct and on the left side into the thoracic duct" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- LA: "Ductus lymphaticus dexter"
	- ES:

# A12.4.01.007
- ## Term
	- EN: "Thoracic duct"
	- LA: "Ductus thoracicus"
	- ES: "Conducto torácico"
- ## Data
	- Anatomy
		- Constitution
        - Conformation
            - Origin
				- Lumbar trunk
				- Cisterna chyli
            - Collaterals
				- Intercostal nodes
				- Juxta-vertebral nodes
				- Posterior mediastinal nodes
            - Joins
				- Left internal jugular vein
				- Left subclavian vein
- ## Definition:
	- "the main trunk of the system of lymphatic vessels that lies along the front of the spinal column, extends from a dilatation behind the aorta and opposite the second lumbar vertebra up through the thorax where it turns to the left and opens into the left subclavian vein, and receives chyle from the intestine and lymph from the abdomen, the lower limbs, and the entire left side of the body \u2014called also left lymphatic duct" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A13.0.00.000
- ## Term
	- EN: "Lymphoid system"
	- LA: "Systema lymphoideum"
	- ES: "Sisema linfatico"
- ## Definition:
	- "the part of the circulatory system that is concerned especially with collecting fluids and proteins that have escaped from cells and tissues and returning them to the blood, with the phagocytic removal of cellular debris and foreign material, and with immune responses, that overlaps and parallels the system of blood vessels in function and shares some constituents with it, and that consists mainly of the thymus, spleen, tonsils, lymph, lymph nodes, lymphatic vessels, lymphocytes, and bone marrow where stem cells differentiate into precursors of B cells and T cells" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

	- EN: "Primary lymphoid organs"
	- LA: "Organa lymphoidea primaria"
	- ES: "Organos linfáticos primarios"
- ## Definition: 

# A13.1.01.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Bone marrow"
	- LA: "Medulla ossium"
	- ES: "Médula ósea"
- ## Definition:
	- "a soft highly vascular modified connective tissue that occupies the cavities and cancellous part of most bones and occurs in two forms:","a whitish or yellowish bone marrow that consists chiefly of fat cells and is found especially in the cavities of the long bones \u2014called also yellow marrow","a reddish bone marrow that contains little fat, is the chief site of red blood cell and blood granulocyte formation, and occurs in the normal adult in cancellous tissue especially of certain flat bones \u2014called also red marrow" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A13.1.02.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Thymus"
	- LA: "Thymus"
	- ES: "Timo"
- ## Data
    - Anatomy
        - Constitution
			- Thymus
        - Configuration
			- Anterior facet
			- Lateral facet
			- Posterior facet
			- Top end
			- Bottom end
        - Conformation
			- Right lobe
			- Left lobe
        - Arteries
			- Internal thoracic artery
			- Inferior thyroid artery
        - Veins
			- Thymic veins
        - Lymph
        - Nerves
- ## Definition:
	- "a glandular structure of largely lymphoid tissue that functions in cell-mediated immunity by being the site where T cells develop, that is present in the young of most vertebrates typically in the upper anterior chest or at the base of the neck, that arises from the epithelium of one or more embryonic branchial clefts, and that gradually decreases in size and activity after puberty" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A13.2.01.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Spleen"
	- LA: "Splen"
	- ES: "Bazo"
- ## Definition:
	- "a highly vascular ductless abdominal organ of vertebrates that resembles a gland in organization but is closely associated with the circulatory system, that plays a role in the final destruction of red blood cells, filtration and storage of blood, and production of lymphocytes, and that in humans is a dark purplish flattened oblong object of a soft fragile consistency lying near the cardiac end of the stomach and consisting largely of blood and lymphoid tissue enclosed in a fibroelastic capsule from which trabeculae ramify through the tissue of the organ which is divisible into a loose friable red pulp in intimate connection with the blood supply and with red blood cells free in its interstices and a denser white pulp chiefly of lymphoid tissue condensed in masses about the small arteries" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A13.2.03.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Capsule"
	- LA: "Capsula"
	- ES: "Cápsula"
- ## Definition:
	- "a membrane or saclike structure enclosing a part or organ","either of two layers or laminae of white matter in the cerebrum:","a layer that consists largely of fibers passing to and from the cerebral cortex and that lies internal to the lentiform nucleus \u2014called also internal capsule" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A13.2.03.003
- ## Term
	- EN: "Trabeculae"
	- LA: "Trabeculae"
	- ES: "Trabécula"
- ## Definition:
	- "a small bar, rod, bundle of fibers, or septal membrane in the framework of a bodily organ or part (as the spleen)","one of a pair of longitudinally directed more or less curved cartilaginous rods in the developing skull of a vertebrate that develop under the anterior part of the brain on each side of the pituitary gland and subsequently fuse with each other and with the parachordal cartilages to form the base of the cartilaginous cranium","any of the intersecting osseous bars occurring in cancellous bone" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A13.2.03.004

	- LA: "Hilum"

# A14.0.00.000
- ## Term
	- EN: "Nervous system"
	- LA: "Systema nervosum"
	- ES: "Sistema nervioso"
- ## Definition:
	- "the bodily system that in vertebrates is made up of the brain and spinal cord, nerves, ganglia, and parts of the receptor organs and that receives and interprets stimuli and transmits impulses to the effector organs" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.0.00.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Nerve fibre"
	- LA: "Neurofibra"
	- ES: "Fibra nerviosa"
- ## Definition: 

# A14.0.00.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Neuron"
	- LA: "Neuron"
	- ES: "Neurona"
- ## Definition:
	- "one of the cells that constitute nervous tissue, that have the property of transmitting and receiving nerve impulses, and that are composed of somewhat reddish or grayish protoplasm with a large nucleus containing a conspicuous nucleolus, irregular cytoplasmic granules, and cytoplasmic processes which are highly differentiated frequently as multiple dendrites or usually as solitary axons and which conduct impulses toward and away from the cell body : nerve cell" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.0.00.003
- ## Term
	- EN: "Perikaryon"
	- LA: "Perikaryon"
	- ES: "Pericarion"
- ## Definition:
	- "cell body" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.0.00.004
- ## Term
	- EN: "Synapse"
	- LA: "Synapsis"
	- ES: "Sinapsis"
- ## Definition:
	- "the place at which a nerve impulse passes from one neuron to another","synapsis" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.0.00.005
- ## Term
	- EN: "Neuroglia"
	- LA: "Neuroglia"
	- ES: "Neuroglía"
- ## Definition:
	- "glia" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Central nervous system"
	- LA: "Pars centralis"
	- ES: "Sistema nervioso central"
- ## Definition:
	- "the part of the nervous system which in vertebrates consists of the brain and spinal cord, to which sensory impulses are transmitted and from which motor impulses pass out, and which supervises and coordinates the activity of the entire nervous system" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.002
- ## Term
	- EN: "Grey matter"
	- LA: "Substantia grisea"
	- ES: "Sustancia gris"
- ## Definition: 

# A14.1.00.003
- ## Term
	- EN: "Nucleus"
	- LA: "Nucleus"
	- ES: "Núcleos"
- ## Definition:
	- "a cellular organelle of eukaryotes that is essential to cell functions (as reproduction and protein synthesis), is composed of nuclear sap and a nucleoprotein-rich network from which chromosomes and nucleoli arise, and is enclosed in a definite membrane","a mass of gray matter or group of nerve cells in the central nervous system","a characteristic and stable complex of atoms or groups in a molecule; especially : ring" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.004
- ## Term
	- EN: "Nucleus of cranial nerve"
	- LA: "Nucleus nervi cranialis"
	- ES: "Núcleos de los nervios craneales"
- ## Definition: 

# A14.1.00.005
- ## Term
	- EN: "Nucleus of origin"
	- LA: "Nucleus originis"
	- ES: "Núcleos de origen"
- ## Definition:
	- "a group of cell bodies in the brain from which nerve fibers of a cranial nerve arise or at which they terminate" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.006
- ## Term
	- EN: "Terminal nucleus"
	- LA: "Nucleus terminationis"
	- ES: "Núcleos de terminación"
- ## Definition: 

# A14.1.00.007
- ## Term
	- EN: "Column"
	- LA: "Columna"
	- ES: "Columna"
- ## Definition:
	- "a longitudinal subdivision of the spinal cord that resembles a column or pillar: as","any of the principal longitudinal subdivisions of gray matter or white matter in each lateral half of the spinal cord","any of a number of smaller bundles of spinal nerve fibers : fasciculus" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.008
- ## Term
	- EN: "Lamina"
	- LA: "Lamina"
	- ES: "Lámina"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thin plate or layer especially of an anatomical part: as","either of two broad, flat plates of bone of a vertebra that is fused with and extends from the pedicle to the median line of the neural arch to form the base of the spinous process and that along with the pedicle forms the posterior part of the vertebral foramen","one of the narrow thin parallel plates of soft vascular sensitive tissue that cover the pododerm of the walls of an animal\u0027s hoof and fit between corresponding horny laminae on the inside of the wall of the hoof" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.009
- ## Term
	- EN: "White matter"
	- LA: "Substantia alba"
	- ES: "Sustancia blanca"
- ## Definition:
	- "neural tissue especially of the brain and spinal cord that consists largely of myelinated nerve fibers bundled into tracts, has a whitish color, and typically underlies the gray matter" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.010
- ## Term
	- EN: "Funiculus"
	- LA: "Funiculus"
	- ES: "Cordón"
- ## Definition:
	- "any of various bodily structures more or less like a cord in form: as","one of the longitudinal subdivisions of white matter in each lateral half of the spinal cord","spermatic cord" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.011
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tract"
	- LA: "Tractus"
	- ES: "Tracto"
- ## Definition:
	- "a system of body parts or organs that act together to perform some function","a bundle of nerve fibers having a common origin, termination, and function and especially one within the spinal cord or brain \u2014called also fiber tract" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.012
- ## Term
	- EN: "Fasciculus"
	- LA: "Fasciculus"
	- ES: "Fascículo"
- ## Definition:
	- "a slender bundle of fibers:","a bundle of skeletal muscle cells bound together by fasciae and forming one of the constituent elements of a muscle","a bundle of nerve fibers that follow the same course but do not necessarily have like functional connections (as in some subdivisions of the funiculi of the spinal cord)" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.013
- ## Term
	- EN: "Commissure"
	- LA: "Commissura"
	- ES: "Comisura"
- ## Definition:
	- "a point or line of union or junction between two anatomical parts (as the lips at their angles or adjacent heart valves)","a connecting band of nerve tissue in the brain or spinal cord" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.014
- ## Term
	- EN: "Lemniscus"
	- LA: "Lemniscus"
	- ES: "Lemnisco"
- ## Definition:
	- "a band of fibers and especially nerve fibers \u2014called also fillet" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.015
- ## Term
	- EN: "Fibre"
	- LA: "Fibra"
	- ES: "Fibra"
- ## Definition:
	- "a thread or a threadlike structure or object: as","a strand of nerve tissue : axon, dendrite","one of the filaments composing most of the intercellular matrix of connective tissue" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.016
- ## Term
	- EN: "Association fibre"
	- LA: "Fibra associationis"
	- ES: "Fibra de asociación"
- ## Definition:

	- ES: "Fibra comisural"
- ## Definition: 

# A14.1.00.018

	- LA: "Fibra projectionis"
	- ES: "Fibra de proyección"
- ## Definition: 

# A14.1.00.019
- ## Term
	- EN: "Decussation"
	- LA: "Decussatio"
	- ES: "Decusación"
- ## Definition:
	- "the action of intersecting or crossing (as of nerve fibers) especially in the form of an X","a band of nerve fibers that connects unlike centers on opposite sides of the nervous system","a crossed tract of nerve fibers passing between centers on opposite sides of the central nervous system : commissure" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.020
- ## Term
	- EN: "Stria"
	- LA: "Stria"
	- ES: "Estría"
- ## Definition:
	- "striation","a narrow structural band especially of nerve fibers","a stripe or line (as in the skin) distinguished from surrounding tissue by color, texture, or elevation" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.021
- ## Term
	- EN: "Reticular formation"
	- LA: "Formatio reticularis"
	- ES: "Formación reticular"
- ## Definition:
	- "a mass of nerve cells and fibers situated primarily in the brain stem and functioning upon stimulation especially in arousal of the organism \u2014called also reticular substance" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.00.022
- ## Term
	- EN: "Ependyma"
	- LA: "Ependyma"
	- ES: 
- ## Definition:
	- "an epithelial membrane lining the ventricles of the brain and the canal of the spinal cord" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Meninges"
	- LA: "Meninges"
	- ES: "Meninges"
- ## Definition:
	- "any of the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord and include the arachnoid, dura mater, and pia mater" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

- ## Term
	- EN: "Pachymeninx"
	- LA: "Pachymeninx"
	- ES: "Paquimeninge"

	- LA: "Leptomeninx"
	- ES: "Leptomeninge"
- ## Definition:
	- "leptomeninges" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.101
- ## Term
	- EN: "Dura mater"
	- LA: "Dura mater"
	- ES: "Duramadre"
- ## Definition:
	- "the tough fibrous membrane lined with endothelium on the inner surface that envelops the brain and spinal cord external to the arachnoid and pia mater, that in the cranium closely lines the bone, does not dip down between the convolutions, and contains numerous blood vessels and venous sinuses, and that in the spinal cord is separated from the bone by a considerable space and contains no venous sinuses \u2014called also dura" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.102
- ## Term
	- EN: "Cranial dura mater"

	- EN: "Falx cerebri"
	- LA: "Falx cerebri"
	- ES: "Hoz del cerebro"
- ## Definition:
	- "the larger of the two folds of dura mater separating the hemispheres of the brain that lies between the cerebral hemispheres and contains the sagittal sinuses" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.104
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tentorium cerebelli"
	- LA: "Tentorium cerebelli"
	- ES: "Tentorio"
- ## Definition:
	- "an arched fold of dura mater that covers the upper surface of the cerebellum, supports the occipital lobes of the cerebrum, and has its posterior and lateral border attached to the skull and its anterior border free" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.105
- ## Term
	- EN: "Tentorial notch"
	- LA: "Incisura tentorii"
	- ES: "Incisura del tentorio"
- ## Definition:
	- "an oval opening that is bounded by the anterior border of the tentorium cerebelli, that surrounds the midbrain, and that gives passage to the posterior cerebral arteries \u2014called also tentorial incisure" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.106

	- EN: "Falx cerebelli"
	- LA: "Falx cerebelli"
	- ES: "Hoz del cerebelo"
- ## Definition:
	- "the smaller of the two folds of dura mater separating the hemispheres of the brain that lies between the lateral lobes of the cerebellum" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.01.107
- ## Term
	- EN: "Diaphragma sellae"
	- LA: "Diaphragma sellae"
	- ES: "Diafragma sellar"
- ## Definition:
	- "a small horizontal fold of the dura mater that roofs over the sella turcica and contains a small opening for passage of the infundibulum" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.02.001
- ## Term
	- EN: "Spinal cord"
	- LA: "Medulla spinalis"
	- ES: "Médula espinal"
- ## Definition:
	- "the thick longitudinal cord of nervous tissue that in vertebrates extends along the back dorsal to the bodies of the vertebrae and is enclosed in the spinal canal formed by their neural arches, is continuous anteriorly with the medulla oblongata, gives off at intervals pairs of spinal nerves to the various parts of the trunk and limbs, serves not only as a pathway for nerve impulses to and from the brain but as a center for carrying out and coordinating many reflex actions independently of the brain, and is composed largely of white matter arranged in columns and tracts of longitudinal fibers about a large central core of gray matter somewhat H-shaped in cross section and pierced centrally by a small longitudinal canal continuous with the ventricles of the brain \u2014called also medulla spinalis" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)

# A14.1.03.001

	- LA: "Encephalon"

	- EN: "Semicircular canals"
	- LA: "Canales semicirculares"
	- ES: "Conductos semicirculares"
- ## Definition:
	- "any of the loop-shaped tubular parts of the labyrinth of the ear that together constitute a sensory organ associated with the maintenance of bodily equilibrium, that consist of an inner membranous canal of the membranous labyrinth and a corresponding outer bony canal of the bony labyrinth, and that in all vertebrates above cyclostomes form a group of three in each ear usually in planes nearly at right angles to each other" - (Mirriam-Webster Dictionary)
